Steve wrote:
Personally, I think there are many defaults of the type system that don't 
make sense...
The default type constraints outputs >= inputs is almost always wrong.
There are many cases where general types are useful and cases
where unknown types are not necessarily type errors...

These are 'built-in' to the type system, and I don't think they should be.
They can all be handled at the level of actors.   For instance, most ports 
could have a default type constraint
type > unknown.  Trigger ports would not.

In the short term, it is probably easier to revert them to type general for 
the release....

At 09:42 AM 1/26/2003 -0800, Edward A Lee wrote:

>Making trigger inputs have type "unknown" doesn't seem to work
>so well... Recall they used to be "general".
>
>The problem is that if you export a trigger input to a trigger
>port of a composite actor, then the type system insists that the
>trigger input has to resolve a type other than unknown, even
>if the outside trigger port is not connected.
>
>There are two possible fixes: Revert the trigger ports to type
>"general" or make the type system smarter so that it allows types
>to resolve to unknown if there is no chance of getting any
>data on the connection...</text></svg></configure>
